Introduction

The highly contagious disease COVID-19 has affected the whole world to some extent, however, there is a wide variation between and within countries in spread and severity of virus cases. The modeling of transmission and spread of any infectious disease relies on several factors. Given the significant economic, social and health consequences of the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, it is vital to identify and investigate the driving factors of the abovementioned variation to implement adequate policy and social response.

It has been established that COVID-19 transmits via human contact, and as a result the common perception is that the disease spreads more rapidly in dense areas than in areas with low population density (Bhadra et al.: 2020). People residing in areas with high population density, such as big cities, have a higher probability to come into regular close contact with others, and so it is common sense to expect metropolitan cities and, in general, countries with high population density to have a larger number of severe cases of COVID-19. However, whether population density has actually promoted the spread and severity of COVID-19 and whether states with higher population density tend consequently to have a higher mortality rate during the pandemic is unknown. Therefore, population density is a variable of interest in examining COVID-19 mortality.

The variation in disease fatality rates between countries might also be linked to variation in states’ expenditure on healthcare infrastructure and the infrastructure’s capacity. Intuitively, countries that allocate a high expenditure on healthcare systems (i.e. have a high percentage of gross domestic product (GDP) spent on healthcare) should have better infrastructure to respond to a public health crisis such as the COVID-19 pandemic by preventing the situation from deteriorating to the point it overwhelms existing resources and healthcare capacity, and increasing preparedness and capacity for intensive care. Healthcare expenditure and associated healthcare capacity should, in theory, directly affect the COVID-19 fatality.

We believe that country preparedness to face a pandemic plays a role in preventing deaths caused as a result of the pandemic. Hence, scores from the Global Health Security Index (2019), a comprehensive assessment of international preparedness to address epidemics/pandemics, biosafety and biosecurity threats, is used as a measure to quantify country preparedness to prevent, suppress, and mitigate an outbreak in context of COVID-19. The scores are calculated from open-source data based upon a framework of 140 questions, organized across 6 categories, 34 indicators, and 85 sub-indicators to assess a country’s capability to prevent and mitigate epidemics and pandemics. The questions are grouped in six categories: prevention, detection and reporting, rapid response, health system, compliance with international norms, and risk environment. For the purpose of this paper, rather than using scores from individual categories, we have decided to use the overall scores to get a broad picture of the relationship between country preparedness and COVID-19 mortality. 

This research paper investigates the effect of population density, healthcare expenditure as percentage of GDP, and country preparedness as measured by the Global Health Security Index 2019 on COVID-19 mortality, as measured by cumulative deaths per million population, in order to account for the difference in population and make a comparison on a standard scale. Establishing the mentioned variables’ plausibility and/or significance in determining the COVID-19 fatality is important for establishing adequate policy response (e.g., potential paradigm shift on GDP healthcare expenditure or stricter policies/higher healthcare expenditure in denser areas).

We considered the use of Case Fatality Ratio (CFR), i.e. the proportion of total deaths from COVID-19 by total number of confirmed cases. We decided to not use CFR as it is highly prone to variations during an ongoing pandemic as it requires individual level data for number of deaths from the disease and the total number of cases, which is less accessible during an ongoing pandemic (WHO, 2020). CFR is more likely to be an accurate estimate in the hindsight of a passed pandemic.

There is a complication with the cumulative death report in that we need to emphasize the limits the analysis of the relationships of the investigating variables, in particular the time variation of when outbreaks started in different countries. The virus took different times to reach the borders of different countries depending on a number of factors, such as state’s migration policies or travel popularity. For example, as noted by Haider et al. (2020), in the early stages of the pandemic Asian countries neighboring China, Europe (UK, France, Russia and Germany), Oceania (Australia) and North America (USA and Canada) were at a greater risk as more people traveled from China to those countries, resulting in greater imported cases. Because we analyze the variables globally by comparing countries, this variation makes comparisons unfair if we do not account for these factors. One way to make comparisons more fair is to limit the analysis to cases occurring to a unified time interval for all countries. We adopt this approach below by limiting the cumulative death cases after June 1st to November 25th. Other limitations are discussed in corresponding section below.

The paper is organised as follows. Section 2 provides a brief literature review of the existing research on population density and healthcare expenditure variables in association with COVID-19 mortality, then, it formulates our hypothesis and expectations for analysis. Section 3 describes the data sourced and Section 4 the methods used for analysis. Section 5 shows our analysis and presents the results. Section 6 offers our conclusions.

Literature Review & Hypothesis

In theory, dense areas lead to more face-to-face interaction among residents, which makes them potential hotspots for the rapid spread of pandemics. So, it is expected that countries with high population density will have a higher spread of Covid-19 and a higher severity of cases, i.e., higher number of cumulative deaths.

However, only a small proportion of existing (limited) research supports this claim. Particularly, the research on how different factors affecting Covid-19 cases in US found that population density is one of the significant impacts on the pandemic spread and mortality. While the conclusion is quite intuitive, the research is limited to US states only and cases prior the summer. On the contrary, other researchers suggest that population density has not adequately predicted the disease’s course in the US over the summer and so does not have an evident relationship with mortality rate. In fact, many public health and urban planning researchers agree that the concentration of people within a certain area does not tell the whole story (Hsu: 2020). Major researches show no or neglectable correlation between population density and Covid-19 fatality in certain states (India, Europe, North America), and others found, even more strangely and counterintuitively, inverse, negative correlation between the variables. Suggested possible explanations to such outcomes are that dense areas may have better access health care facilities, greater resources for intensive care and greater implementations of social distancing and lockdown policies.  

Theoretically, increased levels of healthcare expenditure should improve levels of healthcare capacity and resources because surplus expenditure should allow enhanced investment in infrastructure. Since COVID-19 can have severe symptoms, and severe cases generally require hospitalization to prevent mortality, the ability of a healthcare system to care for severely afflicted patients should play a role in the level of the mortality rate of COVID-19 in a country.

There has been some early research that supports this claim. Specifically, the research involved an analysis of healthcare capacity and healthcare infrastructure, for which healthcare capacity, health expenditure and civil society variables had a positive association with case fatality (Khan & Awan et.al.: 2020). While this conclusion is relatively intuitive and made use of global analysis, it was conducted during a relatively early stage of the pandemic, which poses two major issues. First, it may not have as much information to arrive at its conclusion because it used data from April 2020, which may not be updated, and it may represent a relatively small sample size for the present amount of COVID-19 cases. Second, such an early analysis neglected the nature of healthcare capacity during a pandemic with the potential to have drastic growth.

This is analyzed in another study conducted in Sweden which explains that while healthcare capacity may be adequate for a small fraction of people, should such a number increase drastically (possibly exponentially) over time, potentially due to a lack of disease mitigation and suppression, then such healthcare may not be adequate anymore (Sjödin & Johansson, 2020), As such, healthcare capacity should be evaluated by its ability to respond to this crisis, not to the minute amount of cases present at the time, as explained by another study. This suggests that capacity should be coupled with investments in infrastructure, which is typically available to countries with higher levels of healthcare expenditure. This is explored inresearch that suggested a framework to respond to the pandemic in the aspect of healthcare, for which it predicted the necessity for healthcare infrastructure investments, potentially up to tenfold of the current level, depending on the effectiveness of social distancing and quarantine measures (Dudine, Hellwig & Jahan, 2020), It also suggested that effective quarantine and social distancing may significantly reduce the amount of spending needed for healthcare, and the amount of potential fatalities of the pandemic.

In a similar fashion, preparedness for the healthcare crisis that accompanies a pandemic is also valuable. Risk toward receiving the disease is a key to understanding the level of vulnerability of a country. Infection prevention, infected detection, pandemic response and healthcare sector ability play a valuable role in being able to determine the potential level of distress a country may experience when affected by the pandemic. Reporting norms, and ability to finance the response to a crisis plays a pivotal role in ensuring an effective response. All of these factors require multiple variables to provide a clear picture of a country preparedness. Conveniently, there exists an index, known as the GHSI or the Global Health Security Index that provides a general summary of these factors, already curated by experts.

There have been studies that view GHSI as a valuable tool in for countries to make use of to improve their preparedness for a pandemic. A recent study for example highlights the value that GHSI provides in being able to identify potential weaknesses in healthcare systems in terms of preventing, detecting and responding to outbreaks, taking into consideration relevant social, political and environmental risk factors in the process (Ravi SJ, Warmbrod KL, Mullen L:. et al:. 2020). Knowing the aspects for which a country is weak and strong in terms of healthcare security will better allow a country and its peers to improve and prepare for a pandemic. However, there is also research that while the GHSI may be a simple way to perceive the healthcare security of a country, a potential problem of the index lies in its weighing of its variables. A study that analyses GHSI’s lack of correlation with countries’ COVID-19 detection response time and mortality outcome highlights the importance of appropriate weighting towards certain variables, and the introduction of other variables in order to ensure that the GHSI gives a complete picture of the healthcare scenario of a country. (Haider et.al:. 2020).

Our Hypothesis

We hypothesize that the population density will have a negligible association with the Covid-19 mortality rate because dense areas tend to have greater healthcare expenditure and health care preparedness.

We also hypothesize that the healthcare expenditure (as percentage of GDP) and Global Health Security Index should, in our hypothesis, should have a negative association with cumulative deaths from Covid-19.

Data

Cumulative deaths caused by COVID-19 per million and population density were taken from the “Dashboard: Social and political correlates of Covid-19” project, which uses deaths per day data from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) to generate cumulative COVID-19 case counts. We took population density data from the World Bank and Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO). We limit the cumulative deaths to cases reported after June 1st, 2020 through November 25th, 2020 for the reasons mentioned above.

Health expenditure expressed as a percentage of GDP was sourced from the World Bank, which uses data from the World Health Organization (WHO) Global Health Expenditure database and includes estimates of current health expenditures including healthcare goods and services consumed during each year, but does not include capital health expenditures such as buildings, machinery, and IT. The data used was from 2017, which was the latest available data. Additionally, as noted by Luong (2020), there can be some time lag between health investment and expected outcomes. Secondly, there is potential for reverse causality, i.e., a country may spend more on healthcare due to deteriorating healthcare conditions. Hence, three years serves as an appropriate time lag and prevents reverse causality.

The overall Global Health Security (GHS) Index (2019) score for 195 state parties to the International Health Regulations (IHR [2005]) was scraped from their 2019 report. The scores are calculated from open-source data based upon a framework of 140 questions, organized across 6 categories, 34 indicators, and 85 sub-indicators to assess a country’s capability to prevent and mitigate epidemics and pandemics. The questions are grouped in six categories: prevention, detection and reporting, rapid response, health system, compliance with international norms, and risk environment. The GHSI is a project of the Nuclear Threat Initiative and the Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security and was developed jointly with The Economist Intelligence Unit. The scores are used as a measure of country preparedness to epidemic/pandemic and are evaluated in context of COVID-19. Based on the scores, the countries are categorized as ‘most prepared’ (66.7-100), ‘more prepared’ (33.4-66.6), and ‘least prepared’ (0-33.3).

Methods

We filtered the data to include countries for which all the variables in concern (%GDP spent on healthcare, GHSI score, population density, and cumulative death per million) was available. There were 172 countries which fit this requirement, and the subsequent analysis was done on these countries (n=172).

We calculated point statistics (mean, standard deviation, and median) for all selected variables and used boxplots and scatter plots to perform empirical analysis.

We are also using simple linear regression models which can be expressed as:

\[ Y = \alpha + \beta X \]

where \(Y\) is cumulative deaths (caused by COVID-19) per million, \(\beta\) is the selected variable, and \(\alpha\) is the intercept. The regression model is used under the assumption that the relationship between the two is linear, observations are independent of each other and for any value of \(X\), and the mean of \(Y\) is normally distributed.

Results

Through the exploratory analysis, we found that the median cumulative deaths per million during the period from June 01st to November 25th was approximately 45, while the maximum and minimum was 975 and 0 respectively. The mean and median country values for health expenditure as a % of GDP were almost equal at 6.50% and 6.23% respectively. The difference between the maximum and minimum value (15.92%) shows the vast disparity in healthcare spending from country to country. Among the 175 countries for which the GHS index value was available, only 13 countries were in the most prepared category, 106 in more prepared, and 56 in least prepared. The mean score was 41.8 out of a possible 100 and the median was 38.3. The mean population density was 210 people per square kilometer while the median was 83 people per square kilometers.

The figure below shows the relationship between % of GDP spent on healthcare and the GHS Index overall score. As expected, there is a positive relationship (correlation coefficient = 0.45) with countries with higher health expenditure having higher GHSI score except for a few exceptions. For instance, consider the Marshall Islands (MHL) and Sierra Leone (SLE), which have high % of GDP spent on healthcare but a very low GHSI index score. It is also evident that European nations have a higher percentage of GDP spent on healthcare and correspondingly high GHS Index scores. On the contrary, African nations have a lower percentage of GDP spent on healthcare and correspondingly low GHS Index scores with just one country with a GHSI greater than 60 and only two countries with a % of GDP spent on healthcare greater than 10.

From the initial exploratory analysis, we can already see a rather interesting trend. While it is established that countries with a higher % of GDP spent on healthcare corresponds to higher GHS Index score, and this should in theory mean that countries have higher pandemic preparedness, the data shows that that is not the case. Rather countries with higher index scores and higher spending on healthcare have a higher cumulative deaths caused by COVID-19)per million population. For instance, countries in the more prepared category have median cumulative death as 178 whereas the median for countries in the least prepared category is 11.

The LOESS plot below shows the relationship between cumulative deaths per million and % of GDP spent on healthcare. In general, we see a moderate positive association (correlation coefficient = 0.29) i.e. the cumulative number of deaths per million increases with increased healthcare spending. Peru, Bolivia, Chile, and Argentina are the only countries with cumulative deaths greater than 750 in the period between June 01 and Nov 25.

Discussion

Our findings suggest that countries with higher GHSI scores do not necessarily perform better in terms of mortality caused by COVID-19. This finding is in line with other published studies (Haider N. et al 2020, Boyd MJ. et al 2020). In general, countries with lower GHSI scores seem to have performed better in keeping the effects of the pandemic suppressed. This might be because countries in the least prepared category, predominantly belong to Sub-Saharan Africa and East Asia & Pacific, and have had prior exposure to dealing with pandemics which may have contributed to the countries tackling the pandemic more effectively than expected. Developing countries with lower GDP per capita are likely to spend a greater proportion of their health resources on tackling communicable diseases as it makes up a greater share of disease burden than in developed countries (Roser et. al, 2016). As noted by Khan et. al. (2020), this might mean that the capacity to effectively tackle an infectious disease, such as COVID-19, may be sensitive to decisions about allocation well in advance of the pandemic. In addition, small island states with relatively low GHSI score have seen comparatively less deaths caused by COVID-19, which might be due to less connectivity and the international travel ban rendering non-pharmaceutical interventions more effective.

However, it is also important to note that while countries employing more resource-intensive measures may have prevented higher levels of mortality, it does bring economic repercussions. For example, tourism accounts for a whopping 40% of the GDP of Fiji, a sector which has been rendered almost non-existent after complete border shutdown was imposed recognizing the fact that if local transmission occurred then it would mean certain devastation as the country’s health services were ill-prepared to deal with an outbreak (Leal Filho et al., 2020, p. 5409). A press release by the World Bank (2020) notes that the reduction in economic activities is expected to result in $115 billion in losses and a reduction in GDP per capita growth by nearly 6.0 percent this year in the Sub-Saharan African region.

While it is true that investment in health infrastructure should, in theory, improve the preparedness of countries to tackle epidemics/pandemics, if the measures are not implemented due to socioeconomic or political reasons, such as public trust in government and political polarization, then it is likely that it may be rendered ineffective. Quoting Boyd (2020), “capacity alone is insufficient if that capacity is not fully leveraged.” This holds true in the cases of Latin and South America, the region which has the countries with the highest cumulative deaths caused by COVID-19 per million between June 01 and November 25th. Brazil’s leadership has been criticized for incompetence and even censoring the data when cases were on the rise. In Peru, cases are rising even amidst one of the longest lockdowns in the world, as 73 percent of people work in the informal economy, which requires them to continue working just to sustain their basic needs (Taylor, 2020). It is also likely that developed countries have more resources to conduct extensive testing and systems for reporting data related to COVID-19 - such as number of tests, cases and deaths - which might result in larger figures. Furthermore, developed countries have a greater share of population over the age of 65 and co-morbidities, such as obesity and prevalence of respiratory diseases, which are risk factors of COVID-19.

[1] 0.3121108

The GHSI is a heterogeneous index with various sub-categories, and while analysis based on the overall score does provide some relevant insights it may not be the best indicator of pandemic response. It is also possible that while at present countries with higher GHSI scores are not doing as well, that might not be the case once vaccines are available and they might be able to distribute it more effectively (Boyd MJ. et al 2020). Additionally, the GHSI index relies upon published data which might result in the index not accounting for health measures that are in place, but not recorded or published. While the GHSI provides the first comprehensive assessment of global health security measures, which does provide valuable insights in certain sectors, there are gaps in the assessments which do not fully capture the nuances of health security in the context of a pandemic.

Finally, our analysis shows that higher population density does not imply a higher COVID-19 mortality rate nor lower population density or lower mortality rate, which is consistent with major existing literature and our hypothesis. Although we got a weak association, it does not mean that there is no causality or zero effect of population density on cumulative deaths number. Population density alone certainly affects Covid-19 fatality to some extent, however, as major existing research agree, there are other confounding variables associated with population density that inversely affect the mortality rate and so potentially subdue the density’s negative effect on disease fatality. Such confounding variables might be adoption and adherence of social distancing, mask wearing and lockdown policies, socioeconomic status of residents, capacity for intensive care, etc. (Hamidi et al., 2020). As it is nearly impossible to disentangle density’s effect on deaths cases from other factors, we cannot extend the conclusion of observed correlation to causality.

Limitations

Our analysis of mortality caused by COVID-19 is based on the "reported: deaths using which the cumulative death per million is calculated in the dataset. We understand that the analysis cannot be fully representative of the real COVID-19 mortality, as there is a major concern of underreporting of cases. It is likely that a substantial number of cases go unreported as cases might be asymptomatic or patients might show only mild symptoms, which in some parts of the world, may not qualify them to take a test in order to optimize resources due to limited testing or testing for people at higher risk.

Additionally, people in areas with a lack of proper health infrastructure or extensive testing might not be tested. Another limitation we acknowledge is that not all deaths reported/confirmed are caused directly by COVID-19. WHO for surveillance purposes defines a COVID-19 death, “as a death resulting from a clinically compatible illness in a probable or confirmed COVID-19 case, unless there is a clear alternative cause of death that cannot be related to COVID-19 disease (e.g. trauma). There should be no period of complete recovery between the illness and death.” It is possible that patients might be misdiagnosed as having other diseases with similar symptoms, such as influenza. On the flip side, it is also possible that there might be cases when the deaths reported are caused by other health conditions or illnesses (World Health Organization, 2020). Thus, the reported cumulative death cases from COVID-19 is undercounted in some cases and overcounted in others.

In addition, it is also possible that as the pandemic progresses the relationship between the independent and dependent variables studied might change as new data emerges.

We also note that we are only able to show associations and not causation, and as we have not used any control variables there might be other confounding variables that were not accounted for.

Conclusion

Given the data that we collected, it was observed that there was indeed negligible associations between population density and cumulative COVID-19 mortality. We figured that this was likely due to the general nature of population density, which meant that its effects were heavily clouded by confounding variables, such as adherence of social distancing, mask wearing, lockdown policies, socioeconomic status of residents and capacity for intensive care. While population density provided a clearly accessible statistic, the additional data needed to draw a conclusion from it lead to its inconclusive nature.

On the other hand, our findings show that there is a positive association between healthcare spending as a % GDP and COVID-19 mortality. While this may initially seem counter intuitive, there are other variables that should be taken into consideration when observing the effects of healthcare spending, most notably the age of the people in a country. We observed that the share of the people above 65 in countries was positively associated with healthcare spending in a country - which may suggest that the level of healthcare spending might be a related to spending for the care of older people rather than investments in infrastructure and capacity that we initially thought.

In addition, we also found that the there is a positive correlation between GHSI index and COVID-19 mortality. While we thought this may have been ironic, this confirmed the suspicions we had previously had in reading the literature that speaks of the weaknesses of the GHSI. In our findings, we found that countries from the same continent could be grouped into regions, which was most notable in North America and Africa, which were placed in more prepared and less prepared categories respectively. We think that this may resemble some kind of bias and preference for certain aspects of preparedness which may not have been equitable. As the literature we read outlined, a kind of single standard for its variables that the index appears to use may have indirectly caused countries to be inequitably categorized (Haider et.al:. 2020). While countries in Africa may not have the same top of the line equipment and handbooks as the US, they were already previously affected by other pandemics, which appears to have taught them a pretty good lesson, which served as a great form of preparation. In contrast, while North American countries had better healthcare infrastructure and resources, the priorities of their leadership and their perception of the pandemic contributed to their higher levels of mortality.

In the future, further research can be done to improve the GHSI index, or create a similar index that is better able to gauge preparedness of countries for pandemics. It is also worth analyzing the effects of prevention measures on COVID-19 mortality, as it appears that healthcare alone may not be adequte.
